Here's everything broken down by category — every single thing is free with no card required.

Maps & Location

The browser's built-in navigator.geolocation API handles real-time user location — zero cost, no key. For the map itself, use Leaflet.js with OpenStreetMap tiles. Both are completely open source. For routing (drawing the path from A to B), OpenRouteService has a generous free tier with no card, or you can self-host OpenTripPlanner with free GTFS data.

Transit Data

This is the core of the app. Governments publish GTFS (General Transit Feed Specification) files as open data. For India (Delhi), the Delhi Metro and DTC have public GTFS feeds, and you can find them via data.gov.in or the Transitous global aggregator. These give you bus routes, metro lines, schedules, and stop locations.

Fare Comparison

Build a small static fare table per city (bus = ₹10–25, metro = distance-based, etc.) — this data is public and doesn't change often. For currency formatting based on the user's country, use the browser's built-in Intl.NumberFormat API. No external service needed.

Sustainability Benefits

Keep this as a local JSON file with CO₂ emissions per km per transport mode (e.g. bus = 89g/km, metro = 41g/km, car = 192g/km). Data sourced from Our World in Data and IPCC reports — no API call needed, just static data that rarely changes.

Backend & Hosting

You likely won't need a backend at all initially — most of this can run purely client-side in React. When you're ready to deploy: Vercel (free, no card) or Render (free tier) both work with zero friction.

Dev Tools

VS Code + Cursor (both free), Node.js, npm, Git, GitHub. That's your whole environment — already covered.

